  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "First-order thinking is generative, associative, and uncritical — it produces material. Second-order thinking is analytical, editorial, and critical — it evaluates and shapes material. Peter Elbow introduced this distinction in Writing with Power (1981) to explain why most writers produce neither fluency nor quality: they try to generate and evaluate simultaneously [@elbow1981].\nThe problem is familiar to any writer who stares at a blank page, composing and deleting the same sentence. The internal editor (second-order thinking) intervenes before the generator (first-order thinking) has produced anything to edit. Elbow\u0026rsquo;s solution is to separate the two: write freely first (freewriting), then revise critically later (revision).\n",
  "name": "First-Order and Second-Order Thinking",
  "publisher": {
